df <- df.raw %>% filter(SUBJECT == "POULTRY" & LOCATION == "MEX" & TIME %in% 1994:2014 & MEASURE == "THND_TONNE")
df <- df[, 1:7]

Q5

df.q5 <- df %>% filter(TIME %in% 2004:2013) %>% select(TIME, Value)

df.q5$ft <- 0
df.q5$err <- 0
a <- 0.9

df.q5$ft[1] <- df.q5[1,2]

for (i in 2:nrow(df.q5)) {
  df.q5$ft[i] <- df.q5$ft[i-1] + a * df.q5$err[i-1]
  df.q5$err[i] <- df.q5[i,2] - df.q5$ft[i]
}
# 2014
ft.2014.q5 <- df.q5$ft[10] + a * df.q5$err[10]
act.2014.q5 <- df %>% filter(TIME == "2014") %>% select(Value)
err.2014.q5 <- ft.2014.q5 - act.2014.q5
err.2014.q5
##       Value
## 1 -120.1875
# it is under estimated/predicted since predicted value is lower than actual value. But, its error is smaller than using weighted moving average

df.q6 <- df %>% filter(TIME %in% 2004:2013) %>% select(TIME, Value)

lm.q6 <- lm(df.q6$Value ~ df.q6$TIME)
lm.q6
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = df.q6$Value ~ df.q6$TIME)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)   df.q6$TIME  
##  -181185.96        91.85
for (j in 2014:2016) {
    int <- lm.q6$coefficients[1]
    beta1 <- lm.q6$coefficients[2]
    print(paste0("ft.", j, " = ", int + beta1 * j))
}
## [1] "ft.2014 = 3797.84939999998"
## [1] "ft.2015 = 3889.69836363636"
## [1] "ft.2016 = 3981.54732727271"
int <- lm.q6$coefficients[1]
beta1 <- lm.q6$coefficients[2]
ft.2014.q6 <- int + beta1 * 2014
ft.2015.q6 <- int + beta1 * 2015
ft.2016.q6 <- int + beta1 * 2016

act.2014.q6 <- df %>% filter(TIME == "2014") %>% select(Value)
err.2014.q6 <- ft.2014.q6 - act.2014.q6
err.2014.q6
##     Value
## 1 -3.9836
#it is over estimated/predicted since predicted value is larger than actual value. But, its error is larger than using exponential smoothing

Q7

df.q7 <- df %>% filter(TIME %in% 2004:2014) %>% select(TIME, Value)

# exp smoothing model
df.q7.exp <- df.q7
df.q7.exp$ft <- 0
df.q7.exp$err <- 0
a <- 0.9

df.q7.exp$ft[1] <- df.q7.exp[1,2]

for (i in 2:nrow(df.q7.exp)) {
  df.q7.exp$ft[i] <- df.q7.exp$ft[i-1] + a * df.q7.exp$err[i-1]
  df.q7.exp$err[i] <- df.q7.exp[i,2] - df.q7.exp$ft[i]
}

df.q7.exp
##    TIME    Value       ft       err
## 1  2004 2783.345 2783.345   0.00000
## 2  2005 3029.620 2783.345 246.27500
## 3  2006 3112.794 3004.992 107.80150
## 4  2007 3167.940 3102.014  65.92615
## 5  2008 3261.932 3161.347 100.58461
## 6  2009 3314.587 3251.874  62.71346
## 7  2010 3421.165 3308.316 112.84935
## 8  2011 3532.197 3409.880 122.31693
## 9  2012 3612.905 3519.965  92.93969
## 10 2013 3690.316 3603.611  86.70497
## 11 2014 3801.833 3681.646 120.18750
# MSE for exp smoothing
mse.q7.exp <- mean(df.q7.exp$err^2)
mse.q7.exp
## [1] 13542.37
#linear regression model
df.q7.lr <- df.q7
df.q7.lr$ft <- 0
df.q7.lr$err <- 0

df.q7.lr.sub <- df.q7.lr[1:(nrow(df.q7.lr)-1),]

lm.q7 <- lm(df.q7.lr.sub$Value ~ df.q7.lr.sub$TIME)

coe <- coefficients(lm.q7)

for (i in 1:nrow(df.q7.lr)) {
  df.q7.lr$ft[i] <- coe[1] + coe[2] * df.q7.lr$TIME[i]
  df.q7.lr$err[i] <- df.q7.lr[i,2] - df.q7.lr$ft[i]
}

df.q7.lr
##    TIME    Value       ft        err
## 1  2004 2783.345 2879.360 -96.014764
## 2  2005 3029.620 2971.209  58.411273
## 3  2006 3112.794 3063.058  49.736309
## 4  2007 3167.940 3154.907  13.033345
## 5  2008 3261.932 3246.756  15.176382
## 6  2009 3314.587 3338.605 -24.017582
## 7  2010 3421.165 3430.454  -9.288545
## 8  2011 3532.197 3522.303   9.894491
## 9  2012 3612.905 3614.151  -1.246473
## 10 2013 3690.316 3706.000 -15.684436
## 11 2014 3801.833 3797.849   3.983600
# MSE for linear regression
mse.q7.lr <- mean(df.q7.lr$err^2)
mse.q7.lr
## [1] 1502.641
# based on MSE, MSE of linear regression is much less than that of exponential smoothing. Therefore, I think linear regression model for predictive analysis is better.

#1 moving average model
df %>% ggplot(aes(x=TIME, y=Value)) + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1994, 2014, by = 1)) + geom_line() + labs(title = "Mexico Poultry Consumption 1994-2014 with a forecast for 2014", subtitle = "by moving average", y = "Value (thousand tonnes of carcass weight)") + geom_point(aes(x=2014, y= ft.2014.q3), colour = "red")

#2 weighted moving average
df %>% ggplot(aes(x=TIME, y=Value)) + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1994, 2014, by = 1)) + geom_line() + labs(title = "Mexico Poultry Consumption 1994-2014 with a forecast for 2014", subtitle = "by weighted moving average", y = "Value (thousand tonnes of carcass weight)") + geom_point(aes(x=2014, y= ft.2014.q4), colour = "red")

#3 exponential smoothing
df %>% ggplot(aes(x=TIME, y=Value)) + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1994, 2014, by = 1)) + geom_line() + labs(title = "Mexico Poultry Consumption 1994-2014 with a forecast for 2014", subtitle = "by exponential smoothing", y = "Value (thousand tonnes of carcass weight)") + geom_point(aes(x=2014, y= ft.2014.q5), colour = "red")

#4 linear regression
df %>% ggplot(aes(x=TIME, y=Value)) + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1994, 2014, by = 1)) + geom_line() + labs(title = "Mexico Poultry Consumption 1994-2014 with a forecast for 2014", subtitle = "by linear regression", y = "Value (thousand tonnes of carcass weight)") + geom_point(aes(x= 2014, y= ft.2014.q6), colour = "red")

# Visually speaking, the linear regression is much better since it has less error made (shorter distance between red point and value on the line of actual value in 2014) compared to actual 2014 value based on 2004-2013 data values.
# And we take model performance metrics MSE across all models in to account, linear regression outperforms all the rest models since MSE is substantially less.
